{{unreferenced|date=March 2014}} {{Infobox company | name = Auricchio | logo = Auricchio logo.jpg | caption = | type = Private | genre = | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = 1877 | founder = Gennaro Auricchio | defunct = | location_city = [[Cremona]] | location_country = [[Italy]] | location = | locations = | area_served = | key_people = | industry = [[Dairy products]] | products = [[Italian cheese|Cheese]] | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = | assets = | equity = | owner = Auricchio family | num_employees = 350 | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = [http://www.auricchio.it Auricchio.it] | footnotes = | intl = }} '''Auricchio''' is an [[Italy|Italian]] [[cheese]]-making company, based in [[Cremona]].
==History== Founded in 1877 at [[San Giuseppe Vesuviano]] in the province of [[Naples]], [[Gennaro Auricchio]] was the creator of a special [[rennet]] to produce [[provolone]].
By the 1880s it was exporting cheese to the [[United States]], for stocking in [[Little Italy]]'s shops. This growth created need for new facilities, with a dairy added in [[Cremona]] before 1900.
==Modern production== Today, Auricchio also has plants in: *[[Macomer]] (Nuoro) for [[Pecorino Romano]] D.O.P. and other fresh and mature sheep cheeses *[[Scandiano]] (Reggio Emilia) for production of “[[caciotta]]” (roundish small soft cheese) and “[[ricotta]]” *[[Solignano]] (Parma) specialized in the production of “[[Parmigiano Reggiano]]”
==Products== The company is the largest producer of provolone cheese in Italy, and offers a significant range of dairy products: * [[Provolone]] (sharp, mild and [[Smoking (cooking)|smoked]]) * [[Parmigiano Reggiano]] * [[Grana Padano]] * [[Pecorino Romano]] ([[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|Protected designation of origin]]) * A large assortment of fresh and seasoned [[Pecorino]] cheeses
