{{Japanese name|Yasuda}} The '''Yasuda clan''' was a [[Japan]]ese [[samurai]] kin group in the [[Sengoku period]] and [[Edo period]].<ref name="morikawa61">Morikawa, Hidemasa. (2001). [https://books.google.com/books?id=pCMHQSfAPt4C&pg=PA61&dq= ''A History of Top Management in Japan: Managerial Enterprises and Family Enterprises,'' p. 61].</ref>
==History== The clan was established by Oe Hiromoto.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}
In the Sengoku period, a branch of the Yasuda clan was made responsible for the collection of duties on the cloth trade.<ref>Goldsmith, Brian. (2008). [https://books.google.com/books?id=eOiRmUmQGbYC&pg=PA262&dq=yasuda+clan&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2KKCUcruIabj4AOT7YGwAg&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=yasuda%20clan&f=false ''Amassing Economies: The Medieval Origins of Early Modern Japan, 1450-1700,'' p. 262].</ref>
In modern history, the Yasuda are known as a "financial clan" because of their success in banking.<ref>Lonien, Claude. (2003). [https://books.google.com/books?id=RbT3CC4X-BcC&pg=PA44&dq= ''The Japanese Economic and Social System: From a Rocky Past to an Uncertain Future,'' p. 44].</ref>
